Prediction for performance of computers

Lovdip Singh

Goal of study

To produce and evaluate a predictive model for the performance of computers. https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Computer+Hardware. The data consists of characteristics of computers (available at the time of the study) and a measure of the computer’s performance.

Variance inflation factors

round(diag(solve(cor(machine.df[, 1:6]))), 2)
##  MYCT  MMIN  MMAX  CACH CHMIN CHMAX 
##  1.20  2.90  3.27  1.86  1.97  1.89

The VIFs for the variables are all less than 5, this means that multicollinearity should not be a problem with these regressors.

Pairwise plot

pairs20x(machine.df)

  • PRP is right skewed, therefore predicting the log of PRP makes sense.
  • The relationship between most of the variables appears to be linear.
  • Most of the explanatory variables do not appear to be strongly correlated with each other.
  • The relationship between MYCT alone and the other variables appears to the weakest.
  • There are some unusual data points

Model fitting

fit1 <- lm(PRP~., data=machine.df)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit1)

There is some curvature in the model that needs to be addressed

Box Cox plot

library(MASS)
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
boxcox(fit1)

The Box Cox plot reveals that a log transformation is appropriate.

GAM plot

library(mgcv)
## Loading required package: nlme
## This is mgcv 1.8-33. For overview type 'help("mgcv-package")'.
gam1=gam(log(PRP)~s(MYCT)+s(MMIN)+s(MMAX)+s(CACH)+s(CHMIN)+s(CHMAX),data=machine.df)
par(mfrow=c(2,3))
plot(gam1)

GAM plot reveals that some variables be addressed as they show curvature. In the next iteration of the model quadratic terms will be added.

Cross validation for top models

predfun.lm <-  function(train.x, train.y, test.x, test.y){
  lm1.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + CHMAX + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + I(MMIN^2) + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm1.fit, test.x)
  out1 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  lm2.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + CHMAX + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm2.fit, test.x)
  out2 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  lm3.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + CHMAX + CHMIN + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + I(MMIN^2) + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm3.fit, test.x)
  out3 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  lm4.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + CHMAX + CHMIN + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm4.fit, test.x)
  out4 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  lm5.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + I(MMIN^2) + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm5.fit, test.x)
  out5 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  lm6.fit <- lm(log(train.y) ~ CACH + I(CACH^2) + MMAX + I(MMAX^2) + MMIN + MYCT, data=train.x)
  ynew <- predict(lm6.fit, test.x)
  out6 <- mean((ynew - log(test.y))^2)
  
  c(out1, out2, out3, out4, out5, out6)
}

library(crossval)
cv.out <- crossval(predfun.lm, X=machine.df[, 1:6], Y=machine.df$PRP, 
                  K=10, B=100, verbose=F)

# MSPE for the models
round(cv.out$stat, 5)
## [1] 0.18334 0.18366 0.18587 0.18627 0.19324 0.19082
# MSPE se for the models
round(cv.out$stat.se, 5)
## [1] 0.00216 0.00212 0.00216 0.00214 0.00225 0.00213

Final model

The first and second models performed similarly, the second model is preferred as it is simpler.

# root of MSPE
(sqrt.mspe <- round(sqrt(cv.out$stat[2]), 5))
## [1] 0.42855
# root of MSPE in non-log space
round(exp(-sqrt.mspe), 5)
## [1] 0.65145
round(exp(sqrt.mspe), 5)
## [1] 1.53503

In the cross validation process this model achieved a MSPE of 0.18366, taking the square root of this gives a value of 0.42855, which is in the units of the predicted value. Transforming this into non-log space reveals that the predicted values were off by a factor of 0.65 to 1.54, on average. This is fairly poor performance using the linear model, for example the predicted PRP could have been 600 when the actual PRP could have been closer to 1000.
